Clouds play a key role in the Earth's climate system, yet many of the processes governing their formation and evolution remain poorly understood. Processes such as condensation, evaporation, mixing, and ice formation occur on scales that are difficult to observe directly and therefore remain an important source of uncertainty in weather and climate models. Stable water isotopes offer a promising way to study these processes. Because isotopes fractionate during phase changes, the isotopic composition of atmospheric water carries information about the history of cloud formation and evolution. At the same time, particle-based cloud models have become powerful tools for investigating cloud microphysics because they explicitly represent the evolution of individual droplets and ice particles. Although stable water isotopes are routinely used to study the atmospheric hydrological cycle, their potential as a quantitative constraint on cloud microphysical processes remains largely unexplored. In particular, it is not known whether isotopic observations contain sufficient information to explain the isotopic state of clouds in a physically consistent way.

The aim of this project is to address this question by developing and validating a new isotope-aware particle-based cloud model. The central objective is to test the concept of isotopic closure, understood here as the ability to reproduce and explain observed isotopic composition using a physically based description of cloud evolution. If isotopic closure can be achieved, isotopic measurements could provide a new observational constraint on cloud processes that are otherwise difficult to quantify. The project combines theoretical development, numerical modelling, and observational analysis. A physically consistent description of isotopic fractionation in water vapour, liquid droplets, and ice particles will be developed and implemented in a cloud model based on the Super-Droplet Method within the open-source PySDM framework. The model will explicitly track the isotopic composition of individual computational particles, allowing isotopic signatures to be linked directly to specific microphysical processes. The simulations will be evaluated using isotopic observations from airborne measurement campaigns and laboratory experiments. By comparing model results with measurements, the project will investigate which cloud processes leave detectable isotopic signatures and assess how strongly isotopic observations constrain cloud properties such as supersaturation, phase partitioning, and mixing.

The project is expected to deliver the first systematic assessment of isotopic closure in a particle-based cloud modelling framework. Beyond providing a new tool for isotope-enabled cloud research, it will improve our understanding of what information isotopic measurements contain about cloud evolution and how this information can be used to test and improve numerical models of cloud microphysics.